commentBody:
@JohnWM 

They make rare appearances, but I haven't encountered one in the 34 years I've been playing in the water here.

PEI benefits(?) from the Gulf Stream and has very warm water compared to NH and ME, so I'm not surprised they see JELLYFISH.

@RozzieGrandma 

Absolutely! M&Ms work great in that regard.  :)


@Nancy J. 

The backronym info is fascinating - thanks! 

@Cas

I'm noticing a trend in the comments: all the posts questioning GORP are from (self-identified) central and western Canadians! Maybe it's mostly a northeastern thing.

@Paul Turner 
Aww, give Stranger another read. When I read it as a MOASA, I found much of it silly and pretentious (like many) of Heinleins ouvres) but some of the societal and religious criticisms of the time ring true even today.
I cringe when I hear people us GROK when they mean understand--misses the sense of truely taking something in. I hope my ashes are turned into a delicious batch of, ahem, magic brownies.

@Alex 

You're seeing "ending" as a verb form, but it's a noun.  An ending with Apple or Obama is CARE.

To behave as a good clue should, you'd have to say "Phrase ending with Apple or Obama" for your interpretation to make sense.  Otherwise, there is no parallelism between clue and answer.

@Vaer 

Had Cindy at first ... then (due to crosses) had to change it to Cindi ... and finally Cyndi!  I'll never forget the spelling of her name now!
I also had Gal Pal first.  The only time I heard girlies is when my sister in law caller her new girl identical twins that.  It fit.

@JayTee 

Weird, the first time I heard it was in the 70s and it was always and forevermore Good Old Raisins and Peanuts (we'd add chocolate chips, too).

As a person above stated, Granola is made of oats.  Do they add extra oats, just floating around?  I don't buy it.

@G 

ISH!

I recall beach closings at Rehoboth when the jellies came through in late summer.

@Jim 

I've never heard of including granola in GORP, so that explanation/backronym doesn't make any sense (to me).

As a kid in the 70's, it just was what it was: I don't recall ever questioning the name or needing an explanation why it was called that. Then again, it was provided in such specific situations, hiking and skiing, that it probably didn't occur to me to question it! Also because chocolate. :)

